# React structure

## Stack

- React with functional components and hooks.
- TypeScript when the project is configured for it; same folder conventions apply for JavaScript.

## Copy

- All user-visible strings live under `src/content/` (single source of truth).
- Components import copy from `src/content/` or receive it via props—no hardcoded UI strings in JSX.
- **Exception:** `src/screens/design-system/**` may hardcode organizer/chrome strings (section titles, token ids, control labels). See `docs/design-system-page.md`. Approved components shown on that page still use `src/content/` for real app UI text.

## Logic vs presentation

- **Presentation** (`*.tsx`): render UI; minimal local UI state (open/closed, focus).
- **Logic** (`src/hooks/`, `src/lib/`): game rules, derived state, side effects, data shaping.
- Screens compose hooks + presentational pieces; avoid fat components mixing both.

## File layout

```
src/
  content/       # all copy
  components/    # approved components only (see docs/components.md)
  screens/       # page-level composition
  hooks/         # logic
  lib/           # pure helpers (optional)
  styles/
    theme.css    # design tokens
```

## Style conventions

- Prefer one obvious pattern over many abstractions.
- Extract a hook when logic is reused or a component would exceed ~80 lines of mixed concerns.
- Prefer named exports for components; keep folder structure flat until growth warrants nesting.
- Avoid barrel re-exports (`index.ts` re-exporting everything) until clearly needed.
- Comments: only non-obvious "why", not "what".
